Group 1 Feedback: 

Feedback for WaveY
The WaveY trivia bot was a fun and engaging single-player experience that was easy to
understand and interact with as the group explained it. The use of a starter command, category
selection, interactive buttons, and visual feedback (such as green for correct answers and red for
incorrect ones) makes the bot very user friendly and visually clear for players which makes the
experience to the game after the demo better for us as users. The welcome message with
instructions helps new users quickly understand how to start playing . One potential
improvement would be adjusting the timeout duration, as it seemed to end a bit quickly and
could interrupt the flow of answering questions, as it was kind of a problem in the demo when
demonstrating it. Overall I really liked the bot itself it was fun creative and the functionalities
seems simple to use and wouldn’t be a burden when using the bot itself
this is feedback from classmates, I should have said
WaveY Bot

WaveY is a trivia game bot with four different categories. The bot starts with a welcome message and then you use /trivia to start the game. I liked how the bot clearly shows feedback. Correct answers show up in green and wrong answers show up in red, which makes it easy to see how you did. The score is shown during the game, and if you get 50% or more correct it shows that you won. I also liked that if the game times out it still ends the game properly and shows your score and best streak. Another good design choice is that the game runs in an isolated environment so other people in the Discord channel can’t interfere. One suggestion would be maybe adding difficulty levels or more rounds so players can make the game more challenging if they want.
WAVEY FEEDBACK
The WAVEY trivia bot has a solid foundation, especially with the session-locking feature that
prevents multiple games from overlapping. One specific opportunity for improvement would be
to expand the scoring system to include a "time-bonus" variable, rewarding players who answer
more quickly to add a layer of difficulty. Additionally, while the exit command is great for user
experience, ensuring the bot can gracefully handle a mid-game disconnection without locking
the user out of a future session would be a good edge-case to test. Overall, the streak-tracking
adds a nice competitive element that makes the single-player experience feel more rewarding
Wavey Feedback:

Trivia Bot, single player trivia game. I really like the UI and the scoring logic this bot provides. The extra features such as the streak and all the funny GIFS are interesting and fun. I do think a Discord Bot with multiple people in a server should be multiplayer or have some features that bring the people together such as maybe a leaderboard. The winning percentage being 50% is low in my opinion and maybe should be increased or provide an option for users to increase it for a more competitive experience. The timeout logic being 30 seconds is fast. I would advise increasing the time, or the bot should provide the user with a pause function to increase the amount of time they have in case they have to go for a while. But I do think this is a fun idea and an amazing project.
WaveY
The bot looks thought through with an interesting gameplay loop and is easy to navigate. It seems
like the timeout features seem to be a little too short (timed out twice), along with this, the rules
seemed to be lengthy compared to the gameplay. I feel like the developers already put effort into
making the loop easy to use and understand, so it might be counterintuitive to be so wordy. Other
than that, the bot looks fun and well-developed.

Group 2 Feedback: 

1.	DocViewer Pages Feedback for WaveY A trivia bot is a classic idea to create. It seems you’ve taken great security measures to prevent glitches and exploits, such as preventing /trivia from running twice and making the 30 second timer before the game ends. Although there should, if not already, be a warning to remind the user to answer before they accidentally spend too long thinking and end the game. Having a 50% threshold for a game to be considered won gives the player a specific objective to aim for. But I think the player should also have the option to continue playing if they want, because otherwise it might feel like their game is cut off in the middle, or they may want to aim for 100%. Overall, your formatting and visuals are really good. It was a good choice to use buttons instead of typing the answer directly into the chat due to aesthetics and the prevention of typos. Annotations
2.	Bot Feedback Feedback - Wavy This trivia bot represents a clear gameplay structure that has a welcome message with rule explanations, category selection as well as timed questions. This helps guide the user through the whole experience. The interactive buttons are used to answer choices instead of typed responses and is a strong design because it reduces the amount of invalid input and improves the usability of the bot. The implementation of the session protection that prevents multiple games running at the same time also improves the stability and prevents potential crashes from repeated commands. There could be an improvement with making the time out message more visually distinct or displaying the correct answer again when the time expires so the players can understand what they missed better but overall this demonstrates really good thoughtful handling of user interaction and game session management
3.	WaveY: The repository shows a well organized Discord bot structure with clear separation between commands, events, and helper utilities, which made it easy to navigate. For example, the src/commands, src/events, and src/helpers directories divide responsibilities well, and the trivia gameplay logic is also separated into helper files such as evaluateAnswer.js, activeTrivia.js, and scoreboard.js. The architecture docs and activity diagram included in the repository also help explain how the event driven flow works when a user runs the /trivia command and how the bot manages sessions through a shared session map. One improvement I think would be further separating the game logic from the Discord interaction logic in files like trivia.js so that question handling, scoring, and answer evaluation are fully isolated from the UI layer of buttons and messages, which would make the gameplay logic easier to test and reuse. Currently, the bot stores active sessions in an in memory map, which works for a single runtime but would reset if the bot restarts, so using a simple persistent store or database could make session tracking and player statistics more reliable over time if that's what they would want. The repository already includes testing and fuzzing components such as the tests directory and the src/fuzzer tools for evaluating answer handling, which is good, but expanding these tests to cover more gameplay scenarios such as streak calculations or edge cases in session handling could further strengthen the reliability of the bot as new features are added. Other than that though not much to say because from the live demo in class, it seemed super solid.

WaveY: Overall, WaveY had a good and effective trivia bot with several categories. It runs through a total of 10 questions which are displayed right after each question is answered. So a player can play to their speed which is a plus, however with the questions taken from a pool of one set of questions, a player might be able to simply save the questions or abuse that there are a total of 20 questions used for the questions it asks. This can be a problem for replayability but it’s a matter of having more questions and categories. The exit works and is good for someone that does not wish to continue. The streaks are also good but maybe having a way for the user to be able to have a way to check how many wins they have to have incentives or a streak for how many games that they have won. Everything works and is functioning and it looks fun to play as it covers several topics.
1.	WaveY: I really liked the WaveY Trivia Discord Bot Game idea. It has clear expectations on rules, how to play the game, and is easy to understand from a user’s perspective. One potential idea for improvement could be adding a section where the player can choose the difficulty level they want to play each round. This way, users can play trivia for all types of questions with levels ranging from easy to hard to impossible for users from all expertise levels. Another idea for improvement could be to give longer explanations to the correct answers to all the questions. With the explanations, players are able to make the game into a learning opportunity, especially in categories like Geography, History, and STEM, and maybe more categories in later user stories. Overall, this game is a really creative idea and I hope to play around with it soon!

Feedback: WaveY I really liked your discord bot. It is similar to my group’s bot where we play a trivia game and that the game is solo-player. Some features that I saw was that if you tried to start the game when the game has already started, it tells you that you are already in a game and reroutes you to the question of the current game. I also like how at the end, it shows you a summary of the game, how many questions you got correct and the streak of answers correct. There are some suggestions that I have for you to improve to make the game more interesting or improve functionality. For example, there can be a powerup command that can help users have a higher chance of getting the questions correct like removing an answer, hint, etc. In addition, you can have a command where you can see your full stats anytime during the game, not just at the end when the game ends. Another suggestion that I have is to store the user data like in a database or somewhere to be accessible when you start the bot on discord again, that way you can see past game score.


